to savor in these pages both the phenomenon named Piccaso and the phenomenon named—WINE. On October 5 of this year Pablo Picasso will be 91. We may apply to this out- standing artist the words of Dr. Middleton in Meredith’s The Egoist, when, referring to an ancient Hermitage, he remarked: “(It) has the light of the antique; the merit that it can grow to an extreme old age.” An initially great Bur- gundy, Claret or Port, as it grows more venerable, enlarges in excellence. I recently tasted an 1840 Port awesome in its near-sequoian per-durability. In the same way this immortal Iberian generates more and more new life out of the natural world as his own career intensifies in energy as it unrolls in time.
